    <hr>
    </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row">
    <div class="twelve columns">
    <h4>UNDO</h4>

    <p>You can <strong>undo</strong> the last thing you typed or did in your document by using
    the arrow that circles to the left at the top of an open Word document. The
    symbol looks something like this:</p>

    <img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/wordprocessing/undo.jpg"/>
    <br>

    <p>You may also undo the last thing you typed or did in your document by
    pressing <strong>CTRL + Z</strong>. This is another keyboard shortcut you will need to
    memorize.</p>

    <hr>
    </div>
    </div>


    <div class="row">
    <div class="twelve columns">
    <h4>Any Key</h4>

    <p>This may seem clear to most, but it can be confusing to some people.
    When your computer calls for you to press <strong>"any key,"</strong> that means to press
    any key on the keyboard. There is not a special key labeled "any key."</p>

    <hr>
    </div>
    </div>


    <div class="row">
    <div class="twelve columns">
    <h4>Number Lock Key</h4>

    <p>If you have a number keypad, notice the <strong>Number Lock key (Num Lock)</strong>
    located on the number keypad. It is just like the shift lock key. When it
    is on, you get numbers. When it is off, you get the alternate function
    indicated on the key. You turn this function on and off by pressing the Num
    Lock key. There is sometimes a light on the keyboard indicating when this
    function is turned on.</p>

    <hr>
    </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row">
    <div class="twelve columns">

    <h4>Caps Lock Key</h4>

    <p>Notice the <strong>Caps Lock key</strong> located on the keypad. When it is on, the text
    you type will all be upper case or capital letters. You turn this function
    on and off by pressing the Caps Lock key. There is sometimes a light on the
    keyboard indicating when this function is turned on.</p>

    <hr>
    </div>
    </div>


